msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The sentences are not actually complete, but a period is often used to show "
"a complete thought. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Short sentences or idea phases are less daunting to a young reader. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"It gives them a feeling of accomplishment to finish a sentence unit and "
"understand it."

msgid ""
msgstr "FIRST GRADEÂ Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Unlike the middle of the last century, children are now encouraged to use "
"their imagination in many areas, including reading. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"One of the first things reading programs now encourage children to do is to "
"use mental images based on both the pictures and printed word to help young "
"readers understand the text. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"In a related strategy, they are expected to use the subject that they are "
"reading about, picture captions, the story title, and other clues to aid "
"comprehension and make predictions about what will happen in the story or "
"what a specific character will do."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"When Word Book was first published, phonics was only one of several popular "
"strategies for teaching reading to the youngest children. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"As the new century takes off, phonics has returned to center stage, and "
"children nationally are encouraged to sound words out using basic elements "
"of phonetic analysis such as common letter combinations, letter sounds, and "
"word patterns to figure out unknown words.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr " Social Changes."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Although many first graders have been in all-day kindergarten, some are new "
"to being away from home all day long, and all first graders are new to the "
"sustained periods of concentration that are necessary in the first-grade "
"classroom."

msgid ""
msgstr " In the Classroom."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"While children learn the seasons and the numbers one to ten in kindergarten,"
" the months, days of the week, and numbers over ten generally are introduced"
" in first grade. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Almost all sports are introduced by name at this level. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"However, the technical details and rules are not generally introduced until "
"third grade."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"By the end of kindergarten, most children can sound out any three- or four-"
"letter word. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"However, many of these words (such as eve or dim) are introduced later since"
" they are somewhat abstract. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"(If a word seems overly sophisticated for your young audience, check the "
"word list or the thesaurus sections in this book; the words listed there are"
" taken from publishers' graded material.)Â "

msgid ""
msgstr " Specific Vocabulary Development."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The prefix un is introduced for the simplest of words such as unhappy, "
"unfit, or undo. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The suffix ing is also introduced, and words such as fishing, walking, and "
"reading are common. "

msgid ""
msgstr "The past tense is also introduced. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"This includes irregular forms such as know to knew and was to were, as well "
"as the addition of a simple ed such as ask to asked and walk to walked.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr "Possessives are introduced at the very beginning of the year. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Dad's hat and mother's dress appear along with the other changes mentioned, "
"which give the writer a great deal more flexibility than when writing for "
"the youngest self-readers. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Contractions such as I'd, I'll, I'm, I've, we're, can't, and won't are "
"introduced at this level. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The most commonly used compound words, such as classroom and grandmother, "
"are introduced in first grade, but many schools wait until second grade even"
" if the individual words are understood by the child. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The key seems to be how familiar the reader is with the concept and how "
"often the word is used in their everyday lives.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr " Publishing."

msgid ""
msgstr "The optimal sentence length is still around five to six words. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"However, as with all writing, length should vary throughout your story. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Some publishers are now using longer sentences but use the strategy of "
"breaking them up into five- or six-word lines. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The longest sentence length used in a strictly graded text for this age is "
"ten words. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Parenthetical statements should be avoided. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Sentence length is important because the early reader can become lost in the"
" individual words and have trouble understanding the overall idea. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The constraints on sentence length are eased by the ability to start "
"sentences with such words as and, because, and but. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Sentences at this level need to be whole ideas but do not necessarily need "
"to conform to strictly correct adult standards.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"If the story is written for an adult to read to a child, sentence length is "
"only restricted to that which is comfortably read aloud in one breath. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The vocabulary should be such that the child can easily understand it, but "
"it is not constrained to a graded vocabulary.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"There is a much larger periodical market for the primary group than there is"
" for the very beginning reader. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Very short articles or stories, known as fillers, are popular in magazines. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"These fillers are usually under 500 words and often under 100. One editor "
"told me that \"if you can make brushing your teeth fun, you can make a "
"living the rest of your life.\" Games, riddles, and stories about good "
"health habits, safety, science, and human interest pieces are especially "
"welcome even in the most prestigious periodicals.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"As mentioned earlier, most sports are understood by name at this level and "
"are especially popular in literacy books for older readers. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"There is a great appetite for stories and nonfiction articles about "
"everything from baseball to karate; however, the technical details and rules"
" are not generally introduced until the reader achieves third-grade reading "
"skills.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Like sports, simple mysteries and \"friendly\" ghost stories are popular "
"among first graders or level 1 books. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Many, if not most, of the fiction stories published for six- to eight-year-"
"olds are fantasies, but retelling such classics as The Goose Girl in modern "
"dress is sure to garner rejection slips instead of praise. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Two areas that are popular are stories that show a child being able to help "
"her family or community in a realistic manner and children dealing with "
"minor problems in appropriate ways. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Problems like the death of a goldfish or a divorce is acceptable if it is "
"done with a light touch.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Books for teens and adults learning to read often start at the first-grade "
"level rather than kindergarten. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Most of these books are presented much like those for the young reader but "
"with fewer pictures than those for children, and many are presented in a "
"standard paperback format. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"They primarily feature romance, sports, suspense, nonviolent mysteries, and "
"other high-interest subjects. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"They may also address such practical areas as working, social skills, and "
"legal problems and how to solve them. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The vocabulary, length, and style guidelines are uniform for the level no "
"matter who the end user.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr " Writing Sample."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The following story employs a popular subjectâ€” ghostsâ€”and a popular "
"genreâ€”mystery. "

msgid ""
msgstr "It also takes on a common \"problem\" for kidsâ€”moving. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The sentences are within the ten-word limit, and the words are monosyllabic."
" "

msgid ""
msgstr "Another theme present is adaptation. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"First graders adapt to full days of school work, and Tommy adapts to new "
"surroundings:"

msgid ""
msgstr "Tommy looked at the old house. "

msgid ""
msgstr "There was a ghost in that house. "

msgid ""
msgstr "It was a little ghost, just like Tommy. "

msgid ""
msgstr "He could see the top of its white head. "

msgid ""
msgstr "He could see its eyes. "

msgid ""
msgstr "But that was all. "

msgid ""
msgstr "It had to be a small ghost.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr "\"This is OK. "

msgid ""
msgstr "A ghost is fun,\" he said. "

msgid ""
msgstr "\"Moving here may be OK.\"Â "

msgid ""
msgstr "Tommy did not like to move. "

msgid ""
msgstr "He did not want to move from the city. "

msgid ""
msgstr "But his father was a park ranger. "

msgid ""
msgstr "He worked at a beach park now so they all had to move."

msgid ""
msgstr "Â His father liked the beach. "

msgid ""
msgstr "So did his brother Bob. "

msgid ""
msgstr "His mother loved their house. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Most houses for rangers are not new. "

msgid ""
msgstr "This one was new and it was big. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Tommy was the only one who did not want to live there.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr "\"But a ghost is really OK,\" he said. "

msgid ""
msgstr "\"The old house is OK. "

msgid ""
msgstr "The new house may be OK, too.\""

msgid ""
msgstr "SECOND GRADEÂ Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"In the second and third grades, the smallest number of new words are added "
"to a new reader's vocabulary. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The two grades together add the average number in each of the other grades. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"One change from the earlier edition of the book is the addition of the "
"proper names of the most common dinosaurs. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Previously, even though dinosaurs were very popular with even the youngest "
"child, proper names were not used in graded literature until fifth grade. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"That is still true of the most unusual types, but the most common, such as "
"Stegosaurus or Triceratops, are now introduced here. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Additionally, children are introduced to science, particularly biology and "
"ecology. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Still, overall, this is a time to confirm skills and allow those who were "
"not as ready to catch up.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr " Social Changes."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"One of the major changes common at this age is that most children have "
"become less self-oriented than they were in kindergarten and even first "
"grade. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"As a result, they have stopped generalizing characters, and individual "
"personalities have become important in stories."

msgid ""
msgstr " In the Classroom."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"A beginning study of the solar system is often part of the second-grade "
"curriculum. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The continents and the cardinal directions, north, south, east, and west, "
"are generally taught in school, and there is usually some work with the "
"world map."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Schools introduce their home state, other major states, and a few foreign "
"countries by this level. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"These countries include major powers and nations that are near neighbors of "
"the United States both physically and culturally. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The best known states, such as New York, California, Florida, and Texas, are"
" familiar to the second grader as he learns about the continental United "
"States. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"More explanation or description may be needed in introducing difficult names"
" or lesser known states. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Canada and Mexico, which border the United States, and England, France, and "
"Germany are introduced at this level. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Nations currently in the news are often familiar to the second grader "
"also.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr "Foreign or unusual words begin to be introduced in second grade. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"When including words that are not in the child's vocabulary, it is best to "
"give the definition first and then the word. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Readers tend to skip over unfamiliar words, getting the meaning from the "
"context of the sentence. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Giving the definition first makes it much easier to learn the new word; for "
"example, a large open plain in Africa is called a savanna.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr " Specific Vocabulary Development."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"While some of the most common compound words were introduced in first grade,"
" far more are introduced in second grade. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"At this point, any compound words that are made up of words the children "
"already know may be used. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Going beyond the standard list, you might name a Native American Redhorse or"
" Whitesnake and still be well within the parameters of the age group. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Some compound words in the word lists are listed at a higher grade level "
"than where they usually would be placed. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"These words are listed at the levels at which they were actually used in "
"graded texts. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"However, if the meaning is clear and the word is easily read, it can be used"
" at a lower level."

msgid ""
msgstr " Publishing."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"From this point on, the protagonist of your story should be at least the "
"same age as, and preferably a little older than, the reader. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Since there are few illustrations in easy readers, you need to help your "
"reader identify the characters and give her easy ways to remember each "
"character. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"One way to do this is with tags, actions, gestures, or physical attributes "
"that easily identify the person for the reader. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"One character might constantly be pushing up his glasses when he talks, or "
"another's red hair and freckles may make her memorable.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Mysteries, adventures, and hero stories are very popular at this age. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Vocabulary choice and sentence length are important because most books are "
"aimed at self-readers. "

msgid ""
msgstr "The ideal sentence length is still five or six words. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"However, some publishers have already increased the target sentence length "
"to around ten words. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Long passages of description are still unacceptable. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"There are many reasons to maintain a short sentence length, even if the "
"publisher does not require it. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The child reads one word at a time, then puts the words together to make a "
"whole idea. "

msgid ""
msgstr "The shorter the sentence is, the easier that process becomes. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Thus, it is easier to understand. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The inexperienced reader also gets a sense of accomplishment in successfully"
" finishing and understanding a sentence.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr "Most books run between 1,000 and 1,500 words. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The low end is 500 words, and the high end is 2,000. Most magazines aimed at"
" this age group use stories ranging from 300 to 500 words but welcome short "
"pieces also. "

msgid ""
msgstr "One thousand words is almost certain to be too long for a magazine. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Check your writer's guide lines or Children's Writer's and Illustrator's "
"Market for individual length requirements; remember, publishers generally "
"list the maximum number of words they want. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Second graders seem to be caught in the middle as far as books and magazines"
" are concerned. "

msgid ""
msgstr "They are neither at the beginning nor at the end of a period. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Their interests, reading skills, and egos sometimes make reading picture "
"books unacceptable, and heavily illustrated picture stories are often "
"overlooked because they seem too \"babyish.\" Even though the vocabulary "
"goes beyond second grade, at this point the young reader or easy-to-read "
"book comes into its own. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The more adult presentation appeals to the seven- and eight-year-olds, and "
"their reading skills are generally good enough that they no longer need the "
"support provided by profuse illustrations.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr " Writing Samples."

msgid ""
msgstr "The following story asks the young reader to use her imagination. "

msgid ""
msgstr "It also demonstrates how to introduce a new word, barnacle:"

msgid ""
msgstr "Let's pretend you have an aquarium. "

msgid ""
msgstr "What would you put in it? Would you put a cat in it? No. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Cats don't live in water. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Would you put a dog in it? No. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Dogs don't live in water. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Would you put a barnacle in it? You could. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Barnacles live in water. "

msgid ""
msgstr "But they aren't very pretty. "

msgid ""
msgstr "They are small grayish sea animals. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Would you put a fish in it? Yes. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Fish live in water. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Most fish are pretty. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Some fish are beautiful. "

msgid ""
msgstr "I think I like fish best. "

msgid ""
msgstr "I would put them in my aquarium."

msgid ""
msgstr "THIRD GRADEÂ Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Ecology, which was introduced in a minor way in second grade, is now "
"expanded. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The groups establishing national standards and benchmarks recommend "
"including information on solid waste and recycling. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Quite a few schools have recycling programs, and some clever teachers have "
"the children not only save items like aluminum cans but take a field trip to"
" a recycling plant. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The children see what happens to the materials they collect and can get "
"money for what they have done. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The money can go to a special fund for the school or to buying something for"
" the classroom. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"One of the challenges is to make the children understand why handling trash "
"is important, and interesting stories about this process may well find a "
"variety of markets.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"On a similar note, make sure you check current accepted science before "
"dealing with greenhouse gases, global warming, or other controversial "
"issues. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Just as the fashions in teaching reading were in flux when the last edition "
"of this book was written, opinions on some ecological issues are currently "
"subject to change.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Disaster preparedness is now introduced in third grade along with an "
"increase in health and safety issues. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Natural disasters are more commonly dealt with in the classroom than "
"terrorism. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"One can see the difference that education and preparedness make when "
"studying how communities deal with the same or similar incidents. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Knowing what to do in the case of fire, earthquake, flood, or high winds can"
" save lives, and that educational process often starts in the classroom.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr "Diet is a particular focus now. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Childhood obesity will probably be a political and social issue for ten, or "
"more, years to come. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The students are already familiar with the food pyramid, but knowing what "
"calories are, or carbohydrates, and other issues generally wait for third "
"grade. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"With today's emphasis on weight and health, the \"Fat Albert\" style of hero"
" will probably be a hard sell, but be careful not to make fun of an "
"overweight child. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Personal attack, no matter what the fashion, is unacceptable.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Space, new types of transportation, and a world of future science are also "
"introduced in second and third grades. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Science fiction stories as a genre once waited for fourth or fifth grade, "
"but are now welcome. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The stories should be based on what we can expect in a real future and "
"should explain what things like rotocars are or how they work.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr " Social Changes."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Third graders begin identifying themselves with the world around them "
"through attachments to objects such as toys. "

msgid ""
msgstr "They begin to clearly prefer one thing to another. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"It is just this discovery of taste preferences that creates devoted fans. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Whether it's Star Wars or the Little Mermaid, eight- and nine-year-old third"
" graders are prime markets for toy manufacturers."

msgid ""
msgstr " In the Classroom."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Health, drug, and sex education are started early throughout the United "
"States, and antidrug messages are often a part of the third-grade "
"curriculum. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"In our culture, the word drug has generally taken on the connotation of "
"being a narcotic or other controlled substance. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"In most schools, however, the idea has expanded to include caffeine, "
"tobacco, and alcohol. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"It is wise to stay away from any positive portrayal of these substances, "
"whether your work is aimed at an academic or popular market. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The word medicine is generally used to specify the proper use of controlled "
"substances."

msgid ""
msgstr "Third graders do a lot of in-class reading and group reading. "

msgid ""
msgstr "One of the popular classroom subjects is sports. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The details, rules, and technical aspects of sports begin to be introduced "
"at this level, and sports will remain a high-interest subject throughout all"
" children's and young adult markets. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Another ongoing interest is in mystery stories. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"While they are one of the most popular genres for young readers, there are a"
" few rules you need to know. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Too much violence is generally unacceptable for any juvenile writing. "

msgid ""
msgstr "For preteens, murder is out, and so are most dead bodies. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The only corpses generally are mummies that lend a safely creepy atmosphere "
"to a story. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"For your youngest readers, such as those for this age, think about centering"
" your mysteries on missing treasure or legends and secrets. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Mysteries can actually hone academic skills in an entertaining way by acting"
" as elaborate puzzles the reader must solve.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr " Specific Vocabulary Development."

msgid ""
msgstr "The prefixes dis, ex, and re are added at this level. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"For example, disable, disadvantage, disallow, redo, reset, or any other word"
" already introduced may be used with these prefixes."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Hyphenated words such as part-time, sit-ups, dry-eyed, and age-old are "
"introduced in third grade.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The suffix ment is also introduced at this level: excitement, "
"encouragement.Â Â "

msgid ""
msgstr "You may use the name of almost any body part at this level. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Ankles, knees, shoulders, and even abdomen join the simpler head, arms, and "
"legs previously introduced. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Individual bones and muscles are not understood yet.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr " Publishing."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"By third grade, children have reached the end of the primary reading level. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"They have some experience both reading and choosing books and are beginning "
"to have a good idea of what type of story they like to read."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Your book title helps sell your story both by catching the reader's "
"attention and giving him some idea of what the book is about. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Mysteries or adventures often announce themselves with their title at this "
"level: The Mystery of the Golden Door, The Adventure of Aben-Go-Down. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The title can also announce whether the main character is a boy or a girl: "
"Paula Makes a Mess, Norman Joins the Circus. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"It is true that most book titles are finally chosen by the publisher, but a "
"carefully selected title may be part of what sells your book (and tells your"
" publisher you understand the market) in the first place."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Juvenile publishing is one of the few areas where the commercial rights "
"covered in every book contract may actually be exercised. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Commercial rights cover the use of your story or characters for toys, "
"posters, magnets, and a rather long list of other odd things. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"It doesn't happen often, but there are enough Sponge Bob, Elmo, and Batman "
"t-shirts out there to make one hopeful. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"If you have not reserved commercial rights, all contracts for such items "
"will go through your publisher, no matter how little they seem to resemble "
"your book.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr " Writing Samples."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The following writing sample demonstrates how to introduce words not in the "
"vocabulary:Â "

msgid ""
msgstr "Every day Maria helps her family. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"She feeds the chickens and rolls up the bed mats from the dirt floor of "
"their one-room house. "

msgid ""
msgstr "She also makes a flat bread called tortillas. "

msgid ""
msgstr "The tortillas are cooked on top of the stove.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr "One day Maria woke up early. "

msgid ""
msgstr "She was sure something special was going to happen. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Then she remembered what it was. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Today the men from the town were going to buy bricks in the city. "

msgid ""
msgstr "They would bring back the bricks to build an oven for the pueblo. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Her father would go with them to help.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr "With an oven, they could make bread called bolillos. "

msgid ""
msgstr "They are very much like French rolls. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Maria knew that they could make sweet rolls called pan dulces. "

msgid ""
msgstr "And they could even make cookies and cakes!"

msgid ""
msgstr "FOURTH GRADEÂ Â "

msgid ""
msgstr " Social Changes."

msgid ""
msgstr "Fourth grade is a turning point in a child's development. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Fourth graders are more independent and self-reliant. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Homework is now considered their responsibility rather than one shared with "
"parents. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Most kids are able to read independently, and many begin to read on their "
"own. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Montessori programs often express the enthusiasm of the young reader as "
"\"exploding into reading.\" This describes many fourth graders well. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The jump from the primary readers meant for the first four school years to "
"the more sophisticated books aimed at fourth grade is almost an explosive "
"one. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Series books became popular in third grade because they give the reader "
"confidence. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"In fourth grade, children often read simply for the pleasure of reading, "
"whether they are adventure stories, mysteries, legends, or science fiction. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Children often follow specific authors, such as Judy Blume, and buy book "
"after book in a series such as Harry Potter or the Babysitters Club.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr " In the Classroom."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Fourth grade now covers much, if not most, of the new technology that has "
"developed over the past ten years: digital equipment, new communication "
"systems, smart houses, and the cyber-world. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Thus, you will find some words that were previously listed as fifth or sixth"
" grade words used at this level. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"You can also feel free to use virtually any word from this new vocabulary "
"whether you are talking about podcasting or using a workstation. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Astronomy, geology, paleontology, and other types of science and space are "
"usually taught in fourth or fifth grade. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Science fiction becomes a popular leisure reading subject because it "
"combines the newly acquired academic knowledge with fast-paced adventure.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Many words pertaining to American history are learned in fourth grade, as "
"are the different U.S. "

msgid ""
msgstr "states and the countries of the world. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Many types of plants become familiar at this age also. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The plants given in the word lists are the ones most commonly used in "
"literature."

msgid ""
msgstr "Local history is often introduced at this level. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"This means you can write about geographic areas such as the Rockies, the "
"Great Plains, or New England because a large number of children will be "
"exposed to these topics.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Native American history is also studied in many fourth-grade classrooms. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"It is good policy to use the correct names for indigenous groups rather than"
" using the anglicized or Spanish names. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"For example, it's just as easy for children to learn the name Kummeai for "
"the peaceful Native American tribe that lived in San Diego as it is to learn"
" the Spanish name Degunios. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"It's also just as easy to use Native Americans, Native American Indians, or "
"indigenous peoples, as it is to use Indians. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Your awareness of ethnic language concerns will enrich the experience of "
"your readers.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The new international economy and new breakthroughs in understanding disease"
" have had an impact on health and fitness programs. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Those experts helping shape the new curriculum recommend expanding fourth-"
"grade education to include diet and the beginning of sex education. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Specifically, standard programs now include information on AIDS and HIV, as "
"well as smoking tobacco and drinking alcohol. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Concepts of immunity, genetic links in disease, and disease control are also"
" recommended for the age group.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Words pertaining to foods, cooking, and measurements are introduced by this "
"level and are frequently taught as part of \"fun\" projects in cooking. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Children often make cookies or holiday foods in earlier grades, but now "
"cooking is integrated with mathematics and sociology. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Multicultural festivals at schools often attempt to pull together a great "
"variety of skills in a creative, exciting way.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr " Publishing."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Whether it's space, videogames, or babysitting, both fiction and nonfiction "
"for this age should deal with the special interests and problems of the "
"eight- to twelve-year-old age group. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Most books now range between 20,000 and 40,000 words. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Typical magazine stories run between 700 and 2,000 words, but most "
"publications also use a page or two of special-interest short-shorts under "
"100 words.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Even the most conservative publishers now use the ten-word sentence as a "
"target, with a maximum length of about twenty words. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Even if it's not required, you should not go too far beyond twenty words at "
"a stretch because ideas become more difficult to follow. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Almost all children are still reading one word at a time at this level, and "
"they can actually forget the subject being talked about in a long "
"sentence.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Be careful of using localized terminology, such as specific wildlife or "
"customs unique to an area. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"For example, I once wrote a story on lighter-than-air vehiclesâ€”blimps to "
"us old guys. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"I described an exciting new airship as looking \"like a beach ball being "
"carried on the back of a manta ray.\" My editor thought the description was "
"too localized and kids in the Midwest wouldn't know what a manta ray was. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"We finally decided to say it looked \"like a baseball with a handle "
"attached.\"Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Make sure you check your facts if you are writing about something you "
"remember from a few years ago, but you do not keep up on the subject. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Paleontology is an excellent example. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Good old Brontosaurus had become an Apatosaurus in the 1990s, and the idea "
"that many species may have been warm-blooded and herded in family became "
"widely accepted by the turn of the millennia. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Current opinions may disagree with what was once considered fact.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The elementary level, which covers fourth, fifth, and sixth grades, is the "
"largest of all the markets for children's writers. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Beyond sheer volume, your readers are loyal and appreciative. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"They write fan letters and buy or read all the books a favorite writer "
"produces. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"That loyalty is the reason so many publishers want series books for this "
"age. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"A few publishers won't even look at books that can't be made into a series, "
"and presenting the possibility of a series in a book proposal may be a big "
"plus with any publisher.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Fiction stories should have lots of action, and a carefully crafted modern "
"plot is absolutely necessary at this point. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Many manuscripts are rejected simply because the plots are weak or outdated."
" "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Take the time to find out what hobbies and sports are currently popular, "
"what issues children have to deal with, and what their dreams are; it will "
"go a long way in helping sell your book.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Science fiction is often a great way of explaining science concepts or "
"imparting facts. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"As with any science fiction writing, your \"hard science\" facts must be "
"correct.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr "Nonfiction comes into its own in fourth, fifth, and sixth grades. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Magazines and books specialize in science, mathematics, world events, and "
"much more. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"When you write for these markets, keep track of your source material in case"
" you need to supply a bibliography or support a fact. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Do not submit a bibliography with a manuscript written for a periodical "
"unless you are asked to do so or you know the publisher requires it. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The Children's Writer's and Illustrator's Market listings sometimes note if "
"one is necessary. "

msgid ""
msgstr "When writing a nonfiction book, reference material should be cited."

msgid ""
msgstr " Writing Samples."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The following excerpt demonstrates the fourth grader's new interest in "
"nonfiction and world events:"

msgid ""
msgstr "Towns are like families. "

msgid ""
msgstr "The people who work give money to run the town. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"That year, more than half the people in South Renovo were out of work. "

msgid ""
msgstr "That means they had over 50 percent unemployment. "

msgid ""
msgstr "So the town didn't have much money to spend. "

msgid ""
msgstr "It was so bad even the local YMCA had to shut down.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"It also meant Debra Burrows, the park director, had no money for summer "
"projects. "

msgid ""
msgstr "What she did have was over one hundred kids with nothing to do. "

msgid ""
msgstr "She must have felt like Old Mother Hubbard. "

msgid ""
msgstr "There were only two things left in the playground cupboard. "

msgid ""
msgstr "They had two gallons of white glue and some paper. "

msgid ""
msgstr "So the kids decided to see how long a paper chain they could make.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Later in the same story is this paragraph, capitalizing on the interest of "
"readers learning about measurements:Â "

msgid ""
msgstr "Some kids had odometers on their bikes. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"They used them to measure one-tenth of a mile along the playground fence. "

msgid ""
msgstr "The kids then measured their work in picnic tables (six feet). "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"When they finished a picnic table length, they laid it along the fence. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Eighty-eight picnic tables made one fence length. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The kids made about one fence length, or one-tenth of a mile, each day."

msgid ""
msgstr "FIFTH GRADEÂ Â "

msgid ""
msgstr " Social Changes."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"New studies have shown that many children who have been struggling with "
"reading until now break through in fifth grade. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"For example, about 60 percent of children in the study who had dyslexia and "
"were typically reading at a second-grade level at the beginning of the year "
"jumped to tenth- or twelfth-grade level by the end of the year. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"That jump typifies other, fairly dramatic, changes in a fifth-grader's life."
" "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Fifth graders begin to embark on the stage of growth that changes their "
"focus from home to peers. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"This is fully realized by sixth and seventh grades, but it begins in fifth "
"grade. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Friends' opinions can have as much influence now as a parent's. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Those euphemistically called \"early bloomers\" begin to see secondary "
"sexual characteristics change. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Many students become interested in the opposite sex, whereas others don't "
"see what all the fuss is about. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"In any event, fifth graders become more focused on the outside world than "
"before."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"One way to tap into this new maturity and outside interest is to have "
"students put together \"real\" television broadcasts or other media shows. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Even the smallest schools can now produce packages (a complete program on "
"tape or digital video meant to function as a self-contained, finished unit) "
"of news programs, original plays, or other material to run free of charge on"
" a variety of venues. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"In the past, owing to the low cost and ease of accessibility, most of the "
"time that meant television; however, the possibilities have been greatly "
"expanded. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Streaming online video, Web-based television and radio broadcasting, "
"podcasting, and other new technologies provide great potential for sharing "
"the student's talent with the entire world. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Free Web sites and production programs make these kinds of projects more "
"economically feasible than ever before. "

msgid ""
msgstr "In the Classroom. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Current events generally become part of classroom learning and discussion in"
" fifth grade. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"In most areas, fifth- or sixth-grade students have to memorize the states "
"and their capitals. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The children have a general idea of what each state is like, including their"
" major agricultural and economic products.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Most animals can be recognized at this level; echidnas and platypuses join "
"more familiar animals as good subjects for stories and articles. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Many cities, countries, and sites are introduced by fifth grade. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"If you choose to write about an unusual country, you should be sure to place"
" it geographically; tell your reader that Belize is in Central America and "
"Ghana is on the west coast of Africa.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr "Prehistory is usually studied in fifth grade. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Early man, cave paintings, fire and the development of civilization are "
"often covered. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Science teachers would like to make sure the children know that people did "
"not keep dinosaurs as pets and that they actually know the eras these "
"different species walked the earth. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Even the most unusual dinosaurs, such as Cynognathus, are introduced with "
"their proper name. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"New standards recommend that schools introduce earth sciences such as "
"geology in a more sophisticated manner than in the past, including basic "
"rock types and the scientific names of different geologic ages."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Ecology and environmentalism are major issues in children's magazines, text "
"books, and general literature. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"These topics will remain important areas in children's publishing for many "
"years to come.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Nonfiction subjects that are often introduced in fourth grade in a rather "
"casual way, such as hard science and current events, now become very "
"important both in the classroom and out. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Publishing. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Become familiar with the magazines for this level. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"A large number of magazines cover everything from unusual animals and robots"
" to ongoing peace and war negotiations to killer bees. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Visit your local elementary school to see what magazines they carry."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"For the teacher or writer, producing material for a television program (or "
"the program itself) can engage students and readers in tremendously exciting"
" projects in acting, reading, writing, and researching that have relevance "
"to the children's lives. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"It also provides an excellent and growing market for those who want to write"
" plays for children or work in other dramatic forms. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"It is just as easy to write for this medium correctly (and teach children to"
" write for it correctly) as it is to produce something in a haphazard "
"manner. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Actually, most of the rules for broadcast writing are meant to make the "
"material easier to use during production.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Another alternative market is working with children in the electronic media."
" "

msgid ""
msgstr "That could include computer programs or radio broadcasting.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"One of the ways to make news stories and other academic subjects relevant "
"and interesting is called localization, that is, finding a local angle for "
"the story. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"To do that, you might interview a family from a different country or cover a"
" local ethnic festival. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Localization is highly desirable in the classroom, in broadcast writing, and"
" writing for local periodicals; but you must be careful not to assume that a"
" broader audience will recognize, or be interested in, strictly local "
"references. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"National magazines and books aimed at a national market are leery of any "
"type of localization. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"This is also a good place to become aware of your options that go beyond the"
" \"normal\" forms of publishing. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Many of these alternative markets are grouped under \"electronic rights\" in"
" your book publishing contract. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Unimportant until recently, they include the possibility of your work being "
"included in computer databases or sent by fax. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Some publishers are beginning to sell material only via electronic "
"marketing. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"To find these publishers, look under the syndicates listing in Writer's "
"Market.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr " Writing Samples."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The following excerpt illustrates the technique of sneaking in a history "
"lesson while actually telling a nonfiction story:"

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The tales of lost missions in Mexico are told wherever treasure hunters get "
"together. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The stories usually start off telling about gold and jewels hidden in the "
"missions. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"They often end up being about the curses that are supposed to protect the "
"treasure."

msgid ""
msgstr "Most of these legends are, at best, flights of fancy. "

msgid ""
msgstr "They grew out of daydreams and years of searching. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Yet, the missions themselves are probably real. "

msgid ""
msgstr "More than that, there is some proof the curses are real, too.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr "Later in the same piece, a geography lesson is incorporated:Â "

msgid ""
msgstr "Mountains run down Mexico's west coast, and few people live there. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Even in the south, where there is lots of water, there are only a few place "
"names on the map. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Most of the \"towns\" shown are really only ranches where you can get some "
"rest."

msgid ""
msgstr "SIXTH GRADE AND MIDDLE SCHOOLÂ Â "

msgid ""
msgstr " Social Changes."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Sixth grade is now commonly combined with seventh and eighth grades, or even"
" ninth grade, to create a middle school. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Most middle school students are preteens or young teenagers whose egos "
"depend on being seen as that and not as children. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Their social life is usually centered on groups of friends rather than on "
"the family. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"They have favorite rock bands, and some have their own sources of income. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Even though your reader may seem to have taken a giant step toward growing "
"up, you should stay away from any positive portrayal of drugs, tobacco, "
"alcohol, street language, explicit sex, graphic crime, or violence. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Drunkenness should not be portrayed as humorous.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Because of their own changes, the readers are usually very aware of their "
"appearance and, subsequently, how characters in stories look. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Description is not only acceptable, it's desired.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr " In the Classroom."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"If they haven't already done so, most sixth-grade students are now required "
"to memorize the states, their capitals, and their major economic "
"contributions."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Overall, difficult subjects such as death and divorce are often dealt with "
"at this level in a realistic way. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Sixth grade also includes sex and health education. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"As a result, both in-school and leisure reading materials are often problem "
"oriented.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr " Publishing."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Easy-reading books (also called hi-lo for high interest, low reading) begin "
"to appear at this level. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Most children now have a fairly sophisticated reading vocabulary, and the "
"low achiever has begun to slip between the cracks. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The easy-reading book is one way schools and other programs are trying to "
"prevent that from happening. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"These books are written to cover readers from twelve-years-old through young"
" adults, but they use a controlled vocabulary and sentence length "
"appropriate to the lower vocabulary levels. "

msgid ""
msgstr "These books are short and run from 400 to 1,200 words in length. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"They use a lot of action and dialogue, and often use sports, romance, "
"mystery, and ethnic-urban problems as subjects for their stories.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Besides being a part of the elementary eight- to twelve-year-old market, the"
" sixth grader is more and more often a real part of the high school market, "
"and others in the middle school group are firmly in its grasp. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The high school group officially targets the thirteen- to seventeen-year-"
"olds, but many readers are somewhat younger. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"This group uses an adult vocabulary (as long as it is not too sophisticated)"
" and sentence structure. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Most books range from 25,000 to 55,000 words, and longer lengths are "
"permissible. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Popular fiction subjects include romance, suspense, mild horror, the "
"supernatural, and humor.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"More magazines are aimed at the elementary or middle school group than any "
"other. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Eighty percent of the magazine stories are nonfiction and include age-"
"related problems, dress, dating, interviews, fads, and special interests. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Periodical stories usually range from 1,000 to 3,500 words.Â "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"By sixth grade, it becomes important to the reader to know exactly how a "
"character, especially a leading character, looks. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The just-preteen reader identifies with the leading characters in the books "
"she reads, and her concerns about her own appearance are directly "
"transferred to those characters. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Others in the middle school group want to know how a character dresses, what"
" kind of makeup they wear, how they get around without mom driving, and "
"other issues that help answer very personal questions. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Do be careful when you describe your characters not to make them too much a "
"part of a popular fad either in dress or in speech. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Fads pass quickly, and your book may follow if the reader sees it as \"too "
"last year.\"Â "

msgid ""
msgstr " Writing Samples."

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"The following example shows the increased description present in stories for"
" this age group. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Not only do readers now have longer attention spans, they want descriptive "
"details and like to know how characters look:"

msgid ""
msgstr "Elizabeth thought that it was impossible not to admire him. "

msgid ""
msgstr ""
"Yet, if you looked at his features one at a time, there was little special "
"about him. "

msgid ""
msgstr "He was slim for his 5 feet 10 inches. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Besides his eyes, his gold hair and beard were his best features. "

msgid ""
msgstr "Elizabeth smiled to herself. "

msgid ""
msgstr "She remembered how Bob had grown that beard.Â "

